        "subtopicId": "1.4",
        "title": "Density",
        "digitizedText": "# 1.4 Density\n\n\n\n### What is Density?\nDensity tells us how tightly packed the matter in an object is. A block of iron feels heavier than a block of wood of the exact same size because iron is more dense.\n*   **Definition**: Density is mass per unit volume.\n*   **Equation**: $\\rho = \\frac{m}{V}$ (where $\\rho$ is density, $m$ is mass, and $V$ is volume).\n*   **Units**: $kg/m^3$ or $g/cm^3$.\n\n### Floating and Sinking\n*   An object will **float** in a fluid if its density is **less** than the fluid's density.\n*   An object will **sink** if its density is **greater** than the fluid's density.\n\n\n\n### Measuring Volume to Find Density\nTo find the density of an object, you need its mass (using a balance) and its volume.\n*   **Regular objects** (like a box): Use a ruler to measure length, width, and height. ($V = l \\times w \\times h$).\n*   **Irregular objects** (like a stone): Use the **water displacement method**.\n    1. Fill a measuring cylinder with a known volume of water ($V_1$).\n    2. Submerge the stone in the water.\n    3. Read the new volume ($V_2$).\n    4. The volume of the stone is $V_2 - V_1$.\n\n> \n> [!NOTE]\n> \n> **Examples:**\n> \n> **1. Density of a Metal Block**\n> \n> A metal block has a mass of $1200\\text{ g}$ and dimensions of $10\\text{ cm} \\times 5\\text{ cm} \\times 4\\text{ cm}$. Calculate its density in $\\text{g/cm}^3$.\n> \n> **Solution:**\n> \n> First, find the volume of the block:\n> \n> $V = \\text{length} \\times \\text{width} \\times \\text{height}$\n> \n> $V = 10\\text{ cm} \\times 5\\text{ cm} \\times 4\\text{ cm} = 200\\text{ cm}^3$\n> \n> Now, calculate the density using $\\rho = \\frac{m}{V}$:\n> \n> $\\rho = \\frac{1200\\text{ g}}{200\\text{ cm}^3} = 6\\text{ g/cm}^3$\n> \n> > **2. Volume by Water Displacement**\n> \n> An irregular stone has a mass of $150\\text{ g}$. When placed in a measuring cylinder containing $40\\text{ cm}^3$ of water, the water level rises to $70\\text{ cm}^3$. Calculate the density of the stone.\n> \n> **Solution:**\n> \n> Volume of the stone = Final volume - Initial volume\n> \n> $V = 70\\text{ cm}^3 - 40\\text{ cm}^3 = 30\\text{ cm}^3$\n> \n> Density $\\rho = \\frac{m}{V}$\n> \n> $\\rho = \\frac{150\\text{ g}}{30\\text{ cm}^3} = 5\\text{ g/cm}^3$\n",
