        "subtopicId": "2.1",
        "title": "Kinetic particle model of matter",
        "digitizedText": "# Kinetic Particle Model of Matter\n\n## 1. States of Matter\nSolids, liquids, and gases have distinguishing properties based on the arrangement, separation, and motion of their particles.\n\n> [!NOTE]\n> **Changes of State**\n> - **Melting**: Solid to Liquid\n> - **Boiling / Evaporation**: Liquid to Gas\n> - **Condensation**: Gas to Liquid\n> - **Solidification (Freezing)**: Liquid to Solid\n\n## 2. Particle Model\n- **Solids**: Particles are closely packed in a regular lattice arrangement, vibrating about fixed positions. Strong forces between particles.\n- **Liquids**: Particles are close together but irregularly arranged, moving past each other.\n- **Gases**: Particles are far apart, moving randomly at high speeds. Very weak forces between particles.\n\n> [!IMPORTANT]\n> **Absolute Zero**\n> The lowest possible temperature is **$-273^\\circ\\text{C}$**, known as **absolute zero**. At this temperature, particles have the least kinetic energy.\n\n**Pressure of a Gas:**\nGas pressure is caused by the forces exerted by particles colliding with the surfaces of their container, creating a force per unit area ($p = \\frac{F}{A}$).\n\n**Brownian Motion:**\nThe random motion of microscopic particles (like pollen or smoke) in a suspension is evidence for the kinetic particle model. It is caused by random collisions between the microscopic particles and many light, fast-moving atoms or molecules of the gas or liquid.\n\n## 3. Gases and the Absolute Scale of Temperature\nTemperature in Kelvin (K) and degrees Celsius ($^\\circ\\text{C}$) are related by:\n$$ T \\text{ (in K)} = \\theta \\text{ (in }^\\circ\\text{C}) + 273 $$\n\nFor a fixed mass of gas:\n- **Constant Volume**: Increasing temperature increases the pressure (particles move faster, hit walls harder and more often).\n- **Constant Temperature**: Decreasing volume increases the pressure (particles are more crowded, hitting walls more frequently).\n\n> [!NOTE]\n> **Boyle's Law (Constant Temperature)**\n> $$ pV = \\text{constant} $$\n> For a fixed mass of gas at constant temperature, pressure is inversely proportional to volume.\n\n\n> [!NOTE]\n> **Examples:**\n> \n> **1. Boyle's Law**\n> A fixed mass of gas is kept at a constant temperature. Its initial volume is $400 \\text{ cm}^3$ and its initial pressure is $100 \\text{ kPa}$. The volume is then reduced to $160 \\text{ cm}^3$. Calculate the new pressure of the gas.\n> \n> **Solution:**\n> Using Boyle's Law: $p_1 V_1 = p_2 V_2$\n> $100 \\text{ kPa} \\times 400 \\text{ cm}^3 = p_2 \\times 160 \\text{ cm}^3$\n> $40000 = p_2 \\times 160$\n> $p_2 = \\frac{40000}{160}$\n> $p_2 = 250 \\text{ kPa}$\n> \n> **2. Brownian Motion**\n> Smoke particles in a glass box are observed under a microscope. Explain why the smoke particles are seen to move in a random, zig-zag path.\n> \n> **Solution:**\n> Air molecules are in continuous, random motion.\n> These small, invisible air molecules collide with the larger smoke particles from all directions.\n> The unequal forces from these collisions cause the smoke particles to move in a random, zig-zag path.",
