        "subtopicId": "2.2",
        "title": "Thermal properties and temperature",
        "digitizedText": "# Thermal Properties and Temperature\n\n## 1. Thermal Expansion\nWhen heated at constant pressure, solids, liquids, and gases expand.\n- **Gases** expand the most.\n- **Liquids** expand less than gases.\n- **Solids** expand the least.\n\n*Explanation*: As temperature rises, the motion of particles increases, causing them to push further apart. \n*Everyday applications*: Bimetallic strips in thermostats.\n*Consequences*: Expansion joints in bridges or railway tracks.\n\n## 2. Specific Heat Capacity\nA rise in the temperature of an object increases its **internal energy**. This is because the **average kinetic energy** of all its particles increases.\n\n**Specific Heat Capacity ($c$)** is the energy required per unit mass per unit temperature increase.\n\n- **Symbol**: $c$\n- **Unit**: $\\text{J kg}^{-1} ^\\circ\\text{C}^{-1}$ or $\\text{J}/(\\text{kg } ^\\circ\\text{C})$\n\n> [!NOTE]\n> The higher the specific heat capacity ($c \\uparrow$), the **harder it is for the object to become hot**, and the **harder it is for it to become cold**. A substance with a high $c$ can store a lot of thermal energy without its temperature rising significantly.\n<div align=\"center\">\n<svg class=\"sme-diagram\" width=\"400\" height=\"200\" viewBox=\"0 0 400 200\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\">\n<!-- Frying Pan -->\n<!-- Handle -->\n<rect x=\"220\" y=\"85\" width=\"120\" height=\"20\" rx=\"5\" fill=\"#7f8c8d\" stroke=\"#333\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<text class=\"sme-text\" x=\"240\" y=\"80\" font-family=\"sans-serif\" font-size=\"14\">Material X</text>\n<text class=\"sme-text\" x=\"225\" y=\"125\" font-family=\"sans-serif\" font-size=\"12\" fill=\"#555\">(e.g. Handle)</text>\n<!-- Pan Body -->\n<path d=\"M 60 40 L 80 140 Q 140 160 200 140 L 220 40 Z\" fill=\"#bdc3c7\" stroke=\"#333\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<text class=\"sme-text\" x=\"110\" y=\"100\" font-family=\"sans-serif\" font-size=\"16\">Material Y</text>\n<text class=\"sme-text\" x=\"100\" y=\"180\" font-family=\"sans-serif\" font-size=\"12\" fill=\"#555\">(e.g. Body)</text>\n</svg>\n</div>\n\n### Formulas\nThe energy required to change the temperature is calculated as:\n$$ c = \\frac{\\Delta E}{m\\Delta\\theta} \\quad \\Rightarrow \\quad \\Delta E = mc\\Delta\\theta $$\nWhere:\n- $\\Delta E$ = Change in thermal energy ($\\text{J}$)\n- $m$ = Mass ($\\text{kg}$)\n- $c$ = Specific heat capacity ($\\text{J kg}^{-1} ^\\circ\\text{C}^{-1}$)\n- $\\Delta\\theta$ = Change in temperature\n\n> [!TIP]\n> **Measuring Specific Heat Capacity**\n> To measure $c$ for a solid or liquid, an electrical heater of known power $P$ can be used to heat a mass $m$. The energy supplied is $\\Delta E = Pt$.\n\n## 3. Melting, Boiling and Evaporation\nDuring melting (solid $\\rightarrow$ liquid) and boiling (liquid $\\rightarrow$ gas), there is energy input **without a change in temperature**. \n- The melting and boiling temperatures for pure water at standard atmospheric pressure are $0^\\circ\\text{C}$ and $100^\\circ\\text{C}$ respectively.\n\n> [!IMPORTANT]\n> **Evaporation vs Boiling**\n> - **Evaporation**: Occurs at **any temperature**, only at the **surface** of a liquid. It is the escape of more-energetic particles.\n> - **Boiling**: Occurs only at the **boiling point**, throughout the **entire volume** of the liquid.\n\n**Evaporative Cooling:**\nEvaporation causes cooling because the most energetic particles escape, leaving behind slower particles. This decreases the average kinetic energy (and thus the temperature) of the remaining liquid, cooling any object it is in contact with.\n\nFactors increasing the rate of evaporation:\n1. Higher **temperature**\n2. Larger **surface area**\n3. Greater **air movement** (wind) over the surface\n\n\n> [!NOTE]\n> **Examples:**\n> \n> **1. Specific Heat Capacity**\n> A block of aluminum with a mass of $2.0 \\text{ kg}$ requires $18000 \\text{ J}$ of thermal energy to increase its temperature from $20^\\circ\\text{C}$ to $30^\\circ\\text{C}$. Calculate the specific heat capacity of aluminum.\n> \n> **Solution:**\n> Use the equation: $E = mc\\Delta T$\n> $\\Delta T = 30^\\circ\\text{C} - 20^\\circ\\text{C} = 10^\\circ\\text{C}$\n> $18000 = 2.0 \\times c \\times 10$\n> $18000 = 20 \\times c$\n> $c = \\frac{18000}{20}$\n> $c = 900 \\text{ J}/(\\text{kg}^\\circ\\text{C})$\n> \n> **2. Specific Latent Heat**\n> Calculate the energy required to completely melt $0.50 \\text{ kg}$ of ice at $0^\\circ\\text{C}$. The specific latent heat of fusion of water is $3.3 \\times 10^5 \\text{ J/kg}$.\n> \n> **Solution:**\n> Use the equation: $E = mL_f$\n> $E = 0.50 \\times 3.3 \\times 10^5$\n> $E = 1.65 \\times 10^5 \\text{ J}$",
