        "subtopicId": "2.3",
        "title": "Transfer of thermal energy",
        "digitizedText": "# Transfer of Thermal Energy\n\nThermal energy can be transferred through three primary mechanisms: **Conduction**, **Convection**, and **Radiation**.\n\n## a) Conduction\nConduction is the method of heat transfer in a **solid**. \n- In all solids, it occurs through **atomic or molecular lattice vibrations**.\n- In metals, it is greatly enhanced by the **movement of free (delocalised) electrons**.\n\n> [!TIP]\n> **Why are gases and most liquids bad conductors?**\n> In gases and liquids, particles are further apart and not fixed in a lattice, making the transfer of vibrational energy through collisions very slow. Many non-metallic solids conduct better than insulators but less well than good thermal conductors (metals).\n<div align=\"center\">\n<svg class=\"sme-diagram\" width=\"400\" height=\"150\" viewBox=\"0 0 400 150\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\">\n<!-- Solid Rod -->\n<rect x=\"50\" y=\"50\" width=\"300\" height=\"40\" fill=\"#ecf0f1\" stroke=\"#333\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<!-- Particles -->\n<circle cx=\"70\" cy=\"70\" r=\"15\" class=\"sme-fill-secondary\"/>\n<circle cx=\"110\" cy=\"70\" r=\"15\" class=\"sme-fill-secondary\"/>\n<circle cx=\"150\" cy=\"70\" r=\"15\" fill=\"#e67e22\"/>\n<circle cx=\"190\" cy=\"70\" r=\"15\" fill=\"#f1c40f\"/>\n<circle cx=\"230\" cy=\"70\" r=\"15\" fill=\"#3498db\"/>\n<circle cx=\"270\" cy=\"70\" r=\"15\" fill=\"#3498db\"/>\n<circle cx=\"310\" cy=\"70\" r=\"15\" fill=\"#3498db\"/>\n<!-- Heat Source -->\n<path d=\"M 60 120 L 70 95 L 80 120 Z\" class=\"sme-fill-secondary\"/>\n<text class=\"sme-text\" x=\"50\" y=\"140\" font-family=\"sans-serif\" font-size=\"14\" class=\"sme-fill-secondary\">Heat</text>\n<!-- Free electrons -->\n<circle cx=\"130\" cy=\"60\" r=\"3\" fill=\"#2c3e50\"/>\n<path d=\"M 130 60 L 170 60\" stroke=\"#2c3e50\" stroke-width=\"1\" stroke-dasharray=\"2 2\" fill=\"none\"/>\n<text class=\"sme-text\" x=\"35\" y=\"30\" font-family=\"sans-serif\" font-size=\"16\">A (Hot)</text>\n<text class=\"sme-text\" x=\"320\" y=\"30\" font-family=\"sans-serif\" font-size=\"16\">B (Cold)</text>\n</svg>\n</div>\n\n## b) Convection\nConvection is the method of heat transfer in a **fluid (liquid or gas)** through the **movement of particles** caused by density changes. \n- When heated, the fluid expands and becomes **less dense**, moving **upward**.\n- Cooler, denser fluid moves **downward** to replace it.\n<div align=\"center\">\n<svg class=\"sme-diagram\" width=\"250\" height=\"250\" viewBox=\"0 0 250 250\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\">\n<!-- Beaker -->\n<path d=\"M 50 50 L 50 200 Q 50 220 70 220 L 180 220 Q 200 220 200 200 L 200 50\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"#333\" stroke-width=\"3\"/>\n<path d=\"M 50 80 L 200 80\" stroke=\"#3498db\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<!-- Convection Currents -->\n<!-- Upward -->\n<path d=\"M 125 200 L 125 100\" fill=\"none\" class=\"sme-line-secondary\" stroke-width=\"2\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow-up)\"/>\n<!-- Downward -->\n<path d=\"M 80 100 L 80 200\" fill=\"none\" class=\"sme-line-tertiary\" stroke-width=\"2\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow-down)\"/>\n<path d=\"M 170 100 L 170 200\" fill=\"none\" class=\"sme-line-tertiary\" stroke-width=\"2\" marker-end=\"url(#arrow-down)\"/>\n<defs>\n<marker id=\"arrow-up\" viewBox=\"0 0 10 10\" refX=\"5\" refY=\"5\" markerWidth=\"6\" markerHeight=\"6\" orient=\"auto\">\n<path d=\"M 0 10 L 5 0 L 10 10 z\" class=\"sme-fill-secondary\" />\n</marker>\n<marker id=\"arrow-down\" viewBox=\"0 0 10 10\" refX=\"5\" refY=\"5\" markerWidth=\"6\" markerHeight=\"6\" orient=\"auto\">\n<path d=\"M 0 0 L 5 10 L 10 0 z\" class=\"sme-fill-tertiary\" />\n</marker>\n</defs>\n<!-- Heat -->\n<text class=\"sme-text\" x=\"110\" y=\"240\" font-family=\"sans-serif\" font-size=\"14\" class=\"sme-fill-secondary\">\u2191\u2191 Heat</text>\n</svg>\n</div>\n\n## c) Radiation\nThermal radiation is **infrared radiation** and is emitted by all objects.\n- It **does not require a medium** and can happen in a vacuum.\n\n> [!NOTE]\n> **Thermal Equilibrium**\n> - For an object to be at a constant temperature, it needs to transfer energy away at the **same rate** it receives energy.\n> - The temperature of the Earth is affected by factors controlling the balance between incoming radiation and radiation emitted from Earth's surface.\n\n**Surface Properties:**\nThe rate of emission of radiation depends on the object's **surface temperature** and **surface area**, as well as its colour/texture.\n- **Good Absorber & Emitter**: Black / Dull surfaces\n- **Bad Absorber & Emitter**: White / Shiny / Silver surfaces\n<div align=\"center\">\n<svg class=\"sme-diagram\" width=\"300\" height=\"150\" viewBox=\"0 0 300 150\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\">\n<!-- Sun -->\n<circle cx=\"50\" cy=\"75\" r=\"30\" fill=\"#f1c40f\"/>\n<path d=\"M 85 75 L 105 75 M 75 50 L 90 35 M 75 100 L 90 115 M 50 40 L 50 20 M 50 110 L 50 130\" stroke=\"#f1c40f\" stroke-width=\"3\"/>\n<!-- Radiation Waves -->\n<path d=\"M 120 75 Q 140 50 160 75 T 200 75\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"#e67e22\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<path d=\"M 130 100 Q 150 75 170 100 T 210 100\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"#e67e22\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<path d=\"M 130 50 Q 150 25 170 50 T 210 50\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"#e67e22\" stroke-width=\"2\"/>\n<!-- Object -->\n<rect x=\"230\" y=\"50\" width=\"50\" height=\"50\" fill=\"#333\"/>\n<text class=\"sme-text\" x=\"230\" y=\"120\" font-family=\"sans-serif\" font-size=\"14\">Black Object</text>\n<text class=\"sme-text\" x=\"230\" y=\"140\" font-family=\"sans-serif\" font-size=\"12\" fill=\"#555\">(Absorbs EM waves)</text>\n</svg>\n</div>\n\n## d) Consequences of Thermal Energy Transfer\n- **Everyday applications**: Heating objects like kitchen pans (conduction), heating a room by a convection heater.\n- **Complex applications**: A fire burning wood or coal transfers energy via radiation and convection. A car radiator cools the engine using convection and radiation.\n\n\n> [!NOTE]\n> **Examples:**\n> \n> **1. Conduction in Metals**\n> Why does a metal spoon feel colder than a wooden spoon when both are taken out of a refrigerator?\n> \n> **Solution:**\n> Metal is a good conductor of thermal energy.\n> It conducts heat away from your hand faster than wood, which is an insulator.\n> This rapid loss of heat from your hand makes the metal feel colder.\n> \n> **2. Convection Currents**\n> Explain how a room is heated by a heater placed on the floor.\n> \n> **Solution:**\n> The air next to the heater is warmed, making it expand and become less dense.\n> The warm, less dense air rises towards the ceiling.\n> Cooler, denser air falls to replace it, creating a convection current that transfers heat throughout the room.\n> \n> **3. Thermal Radiation**\n> Two identical cans, one painted dull black and the other shiny white, are filled with the same amount of hot water at $80^\\circ\\text{C}$. Which can will cool down faster and why?\n> \n> **Solution:**\n> The dull black can will cool down faster.\n> Dull black surfaces are better emitters of thermal radiation than shiny white surfaces.\n> Therefore, it will radiate thermal energy to the surroundings at a higher rate.",
