        "subtopicId": "5.1",
        "title": "The Nuclear Atom",
        "digitizedText": "# 5.1 The Nuclear Atom\n\n## Atomic Structure\n\n\nAt the heart of every atom lies the **nucleus**, which contains subatomic particles called **protons** and **neutrons**. Orbiting this nucleus are **electrons**, which travel in specific layers called shells. \n\nHere is a summary of the subatomic particles:\n\n| Subatomic Particle | Charge | Relative Mass |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| **Proton** | Positive (+ve) | 1 |\n| **Neutron** | Neutral (no charge) | 1 |\n| **Electron** | Negative (-ve) | $\\approx$ 0 |\n\n### Key Definitions\n*   **Nucleon Number (Mass Number):** The total sum of protons and neutrons in the nucleus of an atom.\n*   **Proton Number (Atomic Number):** The number of protons in the nucleus. In a neutral atom, this is also equal to the number of electrons.\n\n**Teacher's Note:** Remember that the mass of an electron is so incredibly tiny compared to a proton or neutron that we consider it to be almost zero when calculating the total mass of an atom! \n\n## Isotopes\n\n\n**Isotopes** are atoms of the *same element* that have the *same number of protons* but a *different number of neutrons*. Because they have the same number of protons (and thus electrons), their chemical properties are exactly the same!\n\n*   Example: Sodium-23 ($^{23}_{11}\\text{Na}$) and Sodium-24 ($^{24}_{11}\\text{Na}$). Both have 11 protons, but Sodium-23 has 12 neutrons while Sodium-24 has 13 neutrons.\n\n## Radioisotopes\nA **Radioisotope** is an unstable isotope that releases radioactive particles (radiation) to become more stable.\n\n*   **Examples of Radioisotopes:** Sodium-24, Carbon-13, Carbon-14, Cobalt-60.\n> \n> [!NOTE]\n> \n> **Examples:**\n> \n> **1. Determining atomic composition**\n> \n> An atom of Carbon-14 is represented as $^{14}_{6}\\text{C}$. Determine the number of protons, neutrons, and electrons in a neutral atom of Carbon-14.\n> \n> **Solution:**\n> \n> The proton number (atomic number) is the bottom number: $6$. So, there are $6$ protons.\n> \n> In a neutral atom, the number of electrons equals the number of protons. So, there are $6$ electrons.\n> \n> The nucleon number (mass number) is the top number: $14$. The number of neutrons is the nucleon number minus the proton number: $14 - 6 = 8$ neutrons.\n>\n> \n> **2. Comparing isotopes**\n> \n> Chlorine has two common isotopes: $^{35}_{17}\\text{Cl}$ and $^{37}_{17}\\text{Cl}$. State one similarity and one difference in their atomic structure.\n> \n> **Solution:**\n> \n> Similarity: Both isotopes have $17$ protons (and $17$ electrons in a neutral state).\n> \n> Difference: $^{35}_{17}\\text{Cl}$ has $35 - 17 = 18$ neutrons, whereas $^{37}_{17}\\text{Cl}$ has $37 - 17 = 20$ neutrons. Therefore, they have a different number of neutrons.\n",
