        "title": "Stars and the Universe",
        "digitizedText": "> [!NOTE]\n> **(2) Stars and the Universe**\n\n## The Sun as a Star\nThe Sun is a star of medium size, consisting mostly of hydrogen and helium.\n- It radiates most of its energy in the infrared, visible light, and ultraviolet regions of the electromagnetic spectrum.\n\n**Nuclear Reactions:**\nStars are powered by nuclear reactions that release energy. In stable stars, these nuclear reactions involve the fusion of hydrogen into helium.\n\n### Stars and Galaxies\n- **Galaxies:** Each galaxy is made up of many billions of stars. The Sun is a star in the galaxy known as the Milky Way.\n- Other stars in the Milky Way are much further away from Earth than the Sun.\n- **Light-years:** Astronomical distances can be measured in light-years. One light-year is the distance travelled in (the vacuum of) space by light in one year.\n  - $1 \\text{ light-year} = 9.5 \\times 10^{15} \\text{ m}$\n\n### Life Cycle of a Star\n1. **Formation:** A star is formed from interstellar clouds of gas and dust that contain hydrogen.\n2. **Protostar:** An interstellar cloud collapses and increases in temperature as a result of its internal gravitational attraction, becoming a protostar.\n3. **Stable Star:** A protostar becomes a stable star when the inward force of gravitational attraction is balanced by an outward force due to the high temperature in the center of the star.\n4. **Red Giants / Supergiants:** All stars eventually run out of hydrogen as fuel for the nuclear reaction. Most stars expand to form red giants, and more massive stars expand to form red supergiants when most of the hydrogen in the center of the star has been converted to helium.\n5. **Death of a Star:**\n   - A red giant from a less massive star forms a planetary nebula with a white dwarf star at its center.\n   - A red supergiant explodes as a supernova, forming a nebula containing hydrogen and new heavier elements, leaving behind a neutron star or a black hole at its center.\n   - The nebula from a supernova may form new stars with orbiting planets.\n\n### The Universe\nThe Milky Way is one of many billions of galaxies making up the Universe. The diameter of the Milky Way is approximately 100,000 light-years.\n\n**The Expanding Universe:**\n- **Redshift:** Redshift is an increase in the observed wavelength of electromagnetic radiation emitted from receding stars and galaxies. The light emitted from distant galaxies appears redshifted in comparison with light emitted on Earth.\n- Redshift in the light from distant galaxies is evidence that the Universe is expanding and supports the Big Bang Theory.\n- **CMBR:** Cosmic microwave background radiation (CMBR) is microwave radiation of a specific frequency observed at all points in space. It was produced shortly after the Universe was formed and expanded into the microwave region of the electromagnetic spectrum as the Universe expanded.\n\n> [!NOTE]\n> The speed $v$ at which a galaxy is moving away from Earth can be found from the change in wavelength of the galaxy's starlight due to redshift. The distance $d$ of a far galaxy can be determined using the brightness of a supernova in that galaxy.\n\n**The Hubble Constant ($H_0$):**\nThe Hubble constant $H_0$ is the ratio of the speed at which the galaxy is moving away from the Earth to its distance from the Earth:\n\\[ H_0 = \\frac{v}{d} \\]\n- The current estimate for $H_0$ is $2.2 \\times 10^{-18} \\text{ s}^{-1}$.\n- The equation $\\frac{d}{v} = \\frac{1}{H_0}$ represents an estimate for the age of the Universe and that this is evidence for the idea that all the mass and energy in the Universe was present at a single point.\n\n> [!NOTE]\n> **Examples:**\n> \n> **1. Orbital Speed**\n> A planet orbits a star in a circular path with a radius of $1.5 \\times 10^{11} \\text{ m}$. The time taken for one complete orbit is $3.15 \\times 10^7 \\text{ s}$. Calculate the orbital speed of the planet.\n> \n> **Solution:**\n> Use the orbital speed equation: $v = \\frac{2\\pi r}{T}$\n> $v = \\frac{2 \\times \\pi \\times 1.5 \\times 10^{11}}{3.15 \\times 10^7}$\n> $v \\approx \\frac{9.42 \\times 10^{11}}{3.15 \\times 10^7}$\n> $v \\approx 29900 \\text{ m/s}$\n> \n> **2. Light Years**\n> The distance from Earth to a star is $4.5 \\text{ light-years}$. The speed of light is $3.0 \\times 10^8 \\text{ m/s}$. One year is approximately $3.15 \\times 10^7 \\text{ s}$. Calculate this distance in meters.\n> \n> **Solution:**\n> Distance traveled by light in one year:\n> $d = v \\times t$\n> $1 \\text{ light-year} = 3.0 \\times 10^8 \\times 3.15 \\times 10^7 = 9.45 \\times 10^{15} \\text{ m}$\n> Total distance:\n> $4.5 \\text{ light-years} = 4.5 \\times 9.45 \\times 10^{15} \\text{ m}$\n> Total distance $\\approx 4.25 \\times 10^{16} \\text{ m}$\n\n### Life Cycle of Stars\nNebulae collapse to form protostars, which become main sequence stars. Depending on their initial mass, they follow different paths:\n<div align=\"center\">\n<svg width=\"480\" height=\"240\" viewBox=\"0 0 480 240\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" class=\"sme-diagram\">\n<!-- Lifecycle Flow Chart -->\n<!-- Common Start: Nebula / Protostar -->\n<rect x=\"10\" y=\"100\" width=\"80\" height=\"40\" rx=\"5\" fill=\"none\" class=\"sme-diagram\"/>\n<text class=\"sme-text\" x=\"50\" y=\"125\" class=\"sme-diagram\" font-weight=\"bold\" text-anchor=\"middle\">Nebula</text>\n\n<!-- Arrow to split -->\n<line x1=\"90\" y1=\"120\" x2=\"115\" y2=\"120\" class=\"sme-diagram\"/>\n<polygon points=\"115,120 108,116 108,124\" class=\"sme-diagram\"/>\n\n<!-- Protostar -->\n<rect x=\"115\" y=\"100\" width=\"80\" height=\"40\" rx=\"5\" fill=\"none\" class=\"sme-diagram\"/>\n<text class=\"sme-text\" x=\"155\" y=\"125\" class=\"sme-diagram\" font-weight=\"bold\" text-anchor=\"middle\">Protostar</text>\n\n<!-- Splitting Arrows -->\n<!-- Branch 1: Low-Mass (up) -->\n<path d=\"M 195,120 Q 210,120 210,60 L 220,60\" fill=\"none\" class=\"sme-diagram\"/>\n<polygon points=\"220,60 213,56 213,64\" class=\"sme-diagram\"/>\n\n<!-- Branch 2: High-Mass (down) -->\n<path d=\"M 195,120 Q 210,120 210,180 L 220,180\" fill=\"none\" class=\"sme-diagram\"/>\n<polygon points=\"220,180 213,176 213,184\" class=\"sme-diagram\"/>\n\n<!-- Low-Mass Branch -->\n<rect x=\"220\" y=\"40\" width=\"110\" height=\"40\" rx=\"5\" class=\"sme-diagram\" class=\"sme-axis\"/>\n<text class=\"sme-text\" x=\"275\" y=\"64\" class=\"sme-diagram\" text-anchor=\"middle\">Low-Mass Star</text>\n<text class=\"sme-text\" x=\"275\" y=\"75\" class=\"sme-diagram\" font-size=\"9\" text-anchor=\"middle\">(Red Giant \u2192 White Dwarf)</text>\n\n<!-- High-Mass Branch -->\n<rect x=\"220\" y=\"160\" width=\"110\" height=\"40\" rx=\"5\" class=\"sme-diagram\" class=\"sme-axis\"/>\n<text class=\"sme-text\" x=\"275\" y=\"184\" class=\"sme-diagram\" text-anchor=\"middle\">High-Mass Star</text>\n<text class=\"sme-text\" x=\"275\" y=\"195\" class=\"sme-diagram\" font-size=\"9\" text-anchor=\"middle\">(Supergiant \u2192 Supernova)</text>\n\n<!-- End Stages -->\n<line x1=\"330\" y1=\"60\" x2=\"350\" y2=\"60\" class=\"sme-diagram\"/>\n<polygon points=\"350,60 343,56 343,64\" class=\"sme-diagram\"/>\n<rect x=\"350\" y=\"40\" width=\"110\" height=\"40\" rx=\"5\" fill=\"none\" class=\"sme-diagram\"/>\n<text class=\"sme-text\" x=\"405\" y=\"65\" class=\"sme-diagram\" font-weight=\"bold\" text-anchor=\"middle\">White Dwarf</text>\n\n<line x1=\"330\" y1=\"180\" x2=\"350\" y2=\"180\" class=\"sme-diagram\"/>\n<polygon points=\"350,180 343,176 343,184\" class=\"sme-diagram\"/>\n<rect x=\"350\" y=\"160\" width=\"110\" height=\"40\" rx=\"5\" fill=\"none\" class=\"sme-diagram\"/>\n<text class=\"sme-text\" x=\"405\" y=\"180\" class=\"sme-diagram\" font-weight=\"bold\" text-anchor=\"middle\">Neutron Star</text>\n<text class=\"sme-text\" x=\"405\" y=\"193\" class=\"sme-diagram\" fill=\"#ef4444\" font-size=\"10\" font-weight=\"bold\" text-anchor=\"middle\">or Black Hole</text>\n</svg>\n</div>",
